title: FOIA Request for Records Pertaining to Alicia A. Orzel Arrest on June 30, 2023

communications.subject: Wisconsin Open Records Act Request: FOIA Request for Records Pertaining to Alicia A. Orzel Arrest on June 30, 2023
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Wisconsin Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I request the following records related to the arrest of Alicia A. Orzel on June 30, 2023, at approximately 3:48 p.m. in the town of Edgewater on Lake Chetac:

All body-worn camera footage from deputies involved in the incident.

All dash camera footage from patrol vehicles present during the incident.

Incident and arrest reports detailing the circumstances of the arrest.

Any rear seat camera footage from patrol vehicles transporting Ms. Orzel.

Any other relevant audio or video recordings related to this incident.

This request pertains to charges of felony battery to a sheriff’s deputy and misdemeanor disorderly conduct during a child custody dispute.

I request a fee waiver as disclosure of these records serves the public interest by providing insight into law enforcement procedures and public safety matters, not for commercial gain.

Please provide the requested records in electronic format. If any records are exempt from disclosure, please specify the exemption and release any segregable portions.

Thank you for your attention to this matter.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Police Cam News

March 24, 2025

Police Cam News,

Response to Open Record Request:
I received your Open Records Request regarding:
Incidents involving Alicia A. Orzel, from June 30, 2023 for all BWC, Incident and Arrest Reports, All Dash Camera Footage

The Sheriff's Office did not have Dash Cam at this time of incident. 

We are in receipt of your request and will get this released as soon as possible.
Releasing your record in a more timely manner is now possible with our portal at https://sawyercountywi.nextrequest.  
Here, in our portal you can upload documents, pay online and receive all records in an email. 
Otherwise, we will notify you upon completion and all records will be released upon receiving payment in physical medium format.
Open Records are released in order received
Reproduction cost of $0.25 cents a page, plus $1.92 for each five-minutes, reflecting the assumed staff time involved to scan the document, attach it, and e-mailing, will be assessed. If manual research is required for retrieval, a fee will be determined in addition to the reproduction cost. According to Wisconsin Statute § 19.35(3) (c), we may charge the actual and necessary location costs using the locator’s hourly wage as the base cost.  Redaction cost will apply due to financial gain status. Redaction cost is based on the lowest paid employee’s hourly wage capable of performing the task. A representative of a person(s) on the report will be subject to a $1.92 redaction cost. 
Estimated Cost is $24.79
Due to the high demand for Open Records Request the estimated time is one month.
Please provide a waiver from the person(s) on the record releasing the images of them, and if any, of minor children present in the report, which would save redaction time. 
You will receive a notice upon completion of processing your request of the Open Record, if a response isn’t received within 10 business days, we will consider the request abandoned and closed. 
We accept Check, Money Order or Cash at the Sheriff’s Office.
Make payment payable to: Sawyer County Sheriff

Records will be released upon receiving payment.

title: Library contract request: EBSCO eBooks at Pennsylvania Highlands Community College

communications.subject: Pennsylvania Right to Know Act Request: Library contract request: EBSCO eBooks at Pennsylvania Highlands Community College
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Pennsylvania Right to Know Act, I hereby request the following records:

The most recent contract, governing, base, or master license agreement with EBSCO Information Services (EBSCO Industries, Inc. "EBSCO") relating to the licensing of EBSCO eBooks;

All related terms and conditions, terms of service, amendments, addenda, appendices, attachments, product terms, MOUs, MOAs, data processing agreements, and/or letters of intent; and

All financial documents or records of financial transactions, exchanges or obligations related to the contractual relations with EBSCO for e-book licensing. 

Responsive materials include all contracts, agreements, amendments, appendices, invoices, and any other documents listed above that incorporate language governing terms of use of EBSCO eBooks.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

smhc

communications.communication:
Please accept this email as verification of your request.

Pursuant to Section 902(a) of the Right to Know Law, Pennsylvania Highlands Community College requires an additional 30-days to respond to your request for the following reasons:


     *   Consultation with legal advisors to determine our obligations regarding the requested records.
     *   Identification of available records
     *   Notification of a third-party regarding documents deemed to be responsive to this request
     *   Redaction of responsive records

We will provide a response to you within 30 days (May 16, 2025).  Please be aware that we may have additional clarifying questions regarding this request, so we ask that you remain vigilant in reviewing your emails for our correspondence.

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

All unedited body-worn camera / bodycam recordings related to the following law enforcement critical incident: 

Incident Date: July 20, 2023  
Location: Tramway and Copper NE, Albuquerque, NM  
Victim Name: Emmanuel Galaviz Campos  

I am specifically requesting the unedited body-worn camera recordings captured by all officers present for the full duration of the incident, including audio recordings associated with the footage.  

If any portion of the requested footage must be redacted, I ask that you clearly indicate the portions that have been redacted and provide an explanation of the legal basis for the redactions. If the requested footage is withheld in its entirety, please provide a detailed explanation citing relevant public records exemption(s).

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

Sincerely,

Jeffrey Lamson

communications.subject: Your City of Albuquerque public records request #25-2438 has been submitted.
communications.communication:
City of Albuquerque ************************************************************************ Your record request #25-2438 has been submitted successfully. Greetings: We have received your request for public records and will begin processing your request. This correspondence is intended to acknowledge your request and alert you that it may take up to fifteen days to process your request. NMSA 1978 14-2-8(D). We will be in contact with you as we process your request if we need additional information or if it appears that your request is excessively burdensome and broad. Additionally, please let us know if you have or later acquire documents relating to your request and upload the records into NextRequest. Such additional information has proven to be a useful resource in identifying, locating, and producing additional records. Please be advised, if you are requesting lapel and/or 911 audio from the Albuquerque Police Department (APD), your request may take a significant amount of time to review and provide the records. In lieu of the 911 audio, my office can provide the Computer Aided Dispatch (CAD). The CAD provides information of when the call was received, when and what officers were dispatched, and a description of what happens throughout the incident. In addition, please keep in mind a 5 minute lapel video can take up to 20 minutes to review depending on the type of redactions that are necessary to complete. We will be in contact to discuss ways to narrow your request but you are also welcome to contact us to discuss narrowing options. If you have or later acquire documents relating to your request, please let us know and upload the records into NextRequest. Such additional information has proven to be a useful resource in identifying, locating, and producing additional records. Please do not hesitate to contact us if you would like to know the status of your request, and please communicate all questions and status updates via NextRequest. The Office of the City Clerk reserves the right to charge an advance/deposit fee for materials related to records production and data extraction.  You may access your request by signing into your NextRequest profile at the following website:  https://nextrequest.cabq.gov/users/sign_in  Sincerely, Ethan Watson City Clerk ************************************************************************ Reply to this email or sign in to contact City of Albuquerque.

Change your email settings | Visit our help center

Your request has been assigned to a member of our team for processing. Please know that the City receives a high volume of public records requests and our team is dividing their time among multiple requests. We will strive to contact you approximately every 30-days with either a partial production or a more simple status message update.  If you have multiple requests pending, please let us know if there is you have a specific way you would like us to prioritize your requests. Finally, if you have or later acquire documents relating to your request, please alert us and upload the records into NextRequest. communications.subject: [External Message Added] City of Albuquerque public records request #25-2438
communications.communication:
City of Albuquerque ************************************************************************ A message was sent to you regarding record request #25-2438: Dear Jeffrey Lamson, It is the policy of the City Clerk’s Office to be fully responsive to all requests for public records available under the Inspection of Public Records Act. Our office receives over 12,000 records requests annually, one of our main priorities is to provide those responsive records to your request in a reasonable timeframe and as efficiently as possible. In order to do that we would like to work with you to identify possible ways to narrow your request so that we are only searching for and reviewing those records that contain the information you are looking for. For example, the most time intensive records to review are APD lapel video (a 1-hour recording requires 3-4 hours to review and redact). In most cases, the first responding officer’s lapel video contains the information most requesters seek. If you are able to narrow/tailor your request to that officer’s lapel it can avoid tens to hundreds of hours of review and redaction (which results in additional time needed to respond to your request). If you choose to proactively reach out to our office, we will work with you to better understand your records request and will offer suggestions on ways your request can be further specified to obtain those records you seek as quickly as possible. This invitation to contact our office to narrow your request is voluntary and does not alter any of your rights to inspect public records under the New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act. If you decline our offer to assist in narrowing your request, we will conduct a reasonable search and process your request accordingly.   Finally, if you have or later acquire documents relating to your request, please let us know and upload the records into NextRequest. Such additional information has proven to be a useful resource in identifying, locating, and producing additional records. Sincerely, Dominic Leyba IPRA Tech Office of the City Clerk ************************************************************************ Questions about your request? Reply to this email or sign in to contact staff at City of Albuquerque.
Technical support: See our help page

NOTE: This includes: all but the last four digits of a (1) taxpayer ID number; (2) financial account number; (3) credit/debit card number; (4) driver’s license number; AND (5) all but the year of a person’s date of birth; AND (6) social security number; AND (7) nonelected government employee’s home street address, but not the city state or zip code. I have redacted portion(s) of the records because they are exempt from disclosure under IPRA, NMSA 1978, Section 14-2-1(A) (medical records); Section 14-6-1(A) (medical records); Section 14-2-1(L) (as otherwise provided by law, including NMRA Rule 11-504 (physician-patient and psychotherapist-patient privilege)). See generally 45 C.F.R. §§ 160, 164 (HIPAA). I also determined it was necessary and appropriate to redact/blur the officers’ computer screen videos to avoid potential disclosure of information from the National Criminal Information Center (NCIC). See NMSA 1978, § 14-2-1.2(A)(7) (confidential sources, methods or information); § 14-2-1(L) (as otherwise provided by law, including 28 C.F.R. § 20.21-21, .33). I also redacted certain information which could reveal the identities of undercover police officers or informants. This information is exempt from the Inspection of Public Records Act. See NMSA 1978, § 14-2-1.2(A)(7) (confidential sources, methods or information). If made public, the redacted information would seriously interfere with the effectiveness of criminal investigations and prosecutions, and endanger undercover police officers or informants. I also redacted/exempted certain tactical information pursuant to NMSA 1978, § 14-2-1(I) (tactical response plans or procedures). I also redacted/exempted some confidential law enforcement information. See NMSA 1978, § 14-2-1 (D) (law enforcement records), including §14-2-1.2(A)(7) (confidential sources, methods or information). I have redacted portion(s) of the records because they are exempt from disclosure under IPRA, NMSA 1978, §14-2-1.2(A)(5); and NMSA 1978, Section 14-2-1(L) (as otherwise provided by law, including the City of Albuquerque’s Open Records Ordinance, ROA 1994, Section 2-7-6-5(C)). Responsive records: * * Lapel Videos - Part 1 (shared via Evidence.com at no charge) * Please let us know if the provided videos will satisfy this request or if you still want additional lapel videos. The videos provided include those from the officer most directly related in the incident along with several others. There are approximately 171 lapel videos related to this request. Reviewing videos to make ready for release takes approximately 2-4 times as long as just watching the video itself, so it is a time-consuming process. If you do want additional lapel videos, if you can narrow your request in any way (such as, to specific officers or events), your request may be fulfilled sooner. Otherwise, it will take a significant amount of time for all the videos to be reviewed and made available. Pending records: * * Additional Lapel Videos (if requested) The lapel videos responsive to your request were shared with you via Evidence.com; you will receive a link from Evidence.com which will prompt you to create an account in order to view the videos. If you did not receive the link from Evidence.com, please check your junk/spam folder. Please be advised: you cannot share or forward the link from Evidence.com, because this will void the link and you will not be able to access the videos. Additionally, the videos are only active for 90-days, but you may download them at no charge. This list reflects my understanding of the records that have been completed and processed and the records on which we are still working. If you have a different understanding or believe there are other records outstanding, please contact me as soon as possible.  You will be notified when additional records become available. Thank you for your continued patience. If you have any issues, please contact the City Clerk's office at (505) 924-3650 for assistance in troubleshooting.  Sincerely, CHRISTOPHER C. COCKRELL IPRA Specialist ************************************************************************ Questions about your request? Reply to this email or sign in to contact staff at City of Albuquerque.

communications.subject: Your City of Albuquerque public records request #25-2437 has been submitted.
communications.communication:
City of Albuquerque ************************************************************************ Your record request #25-2437 has been submitted successfully. Greetings: We have received your request for public records and will begin processing your request. This correspondence is intended to acknowledge your request and alert you that it may take up to fifteen days to process your request. NMSA 1978 14-2-8(D). We will be in contact with you as we process your request if we need additional information or if it appears that your request is excessively burdensome and broad. Additionally, please let us know if you have or later acquire documents relating to your request and upload the records into NextRequest. Such additional information has proven to be a useful resource in identifying, locating, and producing additional records. Please be advised, if you are requesting lapel and/or 911 audio from the Albuquerque Police Department (APD), your request may take a significant amount of time to review and provide the records. In lieu of the 911 audio, my office can provide the Computer Aided Dispatch (CAD). The CAD provides information of when the call was received, when and what officers were dispatched, and a description of what happens throughout the incident. In addition, please keep in mind a 5 minute lapel video can take up to 20 minutes to review depending on the type of redactions that are necessary to complete. We will be in contact to discuss ways to narrow your request but you are also welcome to contact us to discuss narrowing options. If you have or later acquire documents relating to your request, please let us know and upload the records into NextRequest. Such additional information has proven to be a useful resource in identifying, locating, and producing additional records. Please do not hesitate to contact us if you would like to know the status of your request, and please communicate all questions and status updates via NextRequest. The Office of the City Clerk reserves the right to charge an advance/deposit fee for materials related to records production and data extraction.  You may access your request by signing into your NextRequest profile at the following website:  https://nextrequest.cabq.gov/users/sign_in  Sincerely, Ethan Watson City Clerk ************************************************************************ Reply to this email or sign in to contact City of Albuquerque.

communications.subject: [External Message Added] City of Albuquerque public records request #25-2437
communications.communication:
City of Albuquerque ************************************************************************ A message was sent to you regarding record request #25-2437: Dear Jeffrey Lamson, It is the policy of the City Clerk’s Office to be fully responsive to all requests for public records available under the Inspection of Public Records Act. Our office receives over 12,000 records requests annually, one of our main priorities is to provide those responsive records to your request in a reasonable timeframe and as efficiently as possible. In order to do that we would like to work with you to identify possible ways to narrow your request so that we are only searching for and reviewing those records that contain the information you are looking for. For example, the most time intensive records to review are APD lapel video (a 1-hour recording requires 3-4 hours to review and redact). In most cases, the first responding officer’s lapel video contains the information most requesters seek. If you are able to narrow/tailor your request to that officer’s lapel it can avoid tens to hundreds of hours of review and redaction (which results in additional time needed to respond to your request). If you choose to proactively reach out to our office, we will work with you to better understand your records request and will offer suggestions on ways your request can be further specified to obtain those records you seek as quickly as possible. This invitation to contact our office to narrow your request is voluntary and does not alter any of your rights to inspect public records under the New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act. If you decline our offer to assist in narrowing your request, we will conduct a reasonable search and process your request accordingly.   Finally, if you have or later acquire documents relating to your request, please let us know and upload the records into NextRequest. Such additional information has proven to be a useful resource in identifying, locating, and producing additional records. Sincerely, Dominic Leyba IPRA Tech Office of the City Clerk ************************************************************************ Questions about your request? Reply to this email or sign in to contact staff at City of Albuquerque.
Technical support: See our help page

communications.subject: Fw: [EXTERNAL] New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Dear Records Requestor:


Your request for information from the New Mexico Educational Retirement Board was forwarded to me. In accordance with the New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act (IPRA), “a written request shall provide the name, address and telephone number of the person seeking access to the records and shall identify the records sought with reasonable particularity.” Section 14-2-8(C) NMSA 1978.


If you will provide me with your name and mailing address, we can begin the process of allowing inspection of the relevant records.


The Inspection of Public Records Act can be found at 14-2-1 through 14-2-12 NMSA 1978.


Thank you.


Amanda Olsen



Amanda Olsen, Paralegal
NM Educational Retirement Board
PO Box 26129
Santa Fe, New Mexico 87502
(505) 476 6133

From: Olsen, Amanda, ERB <Amanda.Olsen@erb.nm.gov>
Sent: Wednesday, June 7, 2023 8:37 AM
To: 147140-15493170@requests.muckrock.com
Subject: Fw: [EXTERNAL] New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence


Dear Records Requestor:



Your request for information from the New Mexico Educational Retirement Board was forwarded to me. In accordance with the New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act (IPRA), "a written request shall provide the name, address and telephone number of the person seeking access to the records and shall identify the records sought with reasonable particularity." Section 14-2-8(C) NMSA 1978.



If you will provide me with your name and mailing address, we can begin the process of allowing inspection of the relevant records.



The Inspection of Public Records Act can be found at 14-2-1 through 14-2-12 NMSA 1978.



Thank you.



Amanda Olsen



Amanda Olsen, Paralegal
NM Educational Retirement Board
PO Box 26129

communications.subject: RE: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Rock,

I am responding to your email yesterday requesting any additional info regarding the source of delays on this request. Please be assured that we make every effort to respond promptly to every request. However, we must also ensure that we are diligent and accurate in our reply. Thus, when obtained, all documents and emails must be reviewed. Additionally, we must rely on the state agency that controls the entire state email system to identify and provide the emails requested. As you can imagine, the process takes time.

As to an estimated response date, in our letter of August 1, 2023, we noted that we intend to respond by September 6, 2023.

Thank you for your patience and please feel free to contact me if you have further questions.

Respectfully,

[cid:image001.png@01D9C623.0D3F7D80]

communications.subject: ATTORNEY CLIENT PRIVILEGED - RE: [EXTERNAL] RE: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Rock and Ms. Burns,

Thank you for your inquiry and please accept our apologies for the delay.

As Mr. Scroggins noted in his August 3, 2023 email regarding our projected response, we always try to be prompt.  But as you might guess, the request references a large number of records.  As he said, we must thoroughly review all records to identify and obtain the responsive documents from both external and internal sources.  It is a complex and time-consuming process.

I am confident that we will have documents ready to provide on or before the December 6th, 2023, date noted in our recent communication.

Thank you for your continued patience!
Regards,
Renee

title: Records Request - Eads and 18th STreet South

communications.subject: Virginia Freedom of Information Act Request: Records Request - Eads and 18th STreet South
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Virginia Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

For the multifamily property known as Crystal Towers and Crytal Flats located at 1600 South Eads Street and 505 18th Street South Arlington VA 22202 with Parcel ID 5-011-010, 35-011-011, 35-011-001, please provide the following information:

Notice and summary of any open/outstanding zoning, building, and/or fire code violations, or written confirmation that none currently exist;
Copies of Certificates of Occupancy, or if none are available, please state the reason for their absence and whether the lack of Certificates of Occupancy will result in any enforcement action; and
Copies of any zoning approval documents, specifically a copy of the Crystal Towers Site Plan #13 and 1720 S Eads Street Site Plan #424

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Tom Nash, a citizen of Virginia, in coordination with Olivia James.

    Copies of any zoning approval documents, specifically a copy of the Crystal Towers Site Plan #13 and 1720 S Eads Street Site Plan #424

    In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Pursuant to your request to receive an estimate in advance, attached is your estimate. No payment is required at this time. 
Please review the estimate and respond to this email letting us know if you accept the charges and wish for us to continue processing your request. If you accept the estimate, a final invoice will be sent to you at the same time as the County’s response to your request.

RE: County Records Request of April 16, 2025, Reference # C006011-041625. 
Dear Tom Nash, 
Your invoice is available for review and payment.  Please see attached or login to the to view details. Arlington County FOIA Center 
Pursuant to Code of Virginia § 2.2-3704(F), the County is permitted to make reasonable charges to cover the County’s actual cost incurred in accessing, duplicating, supplying, or searching for any potential responsive records. 
If you are receiving this invoice but have not received a final response and records responsive to your request, then this invoice is a request for an estimate deposit pursuant to Virginia Code Section 2.2-3704(H) and an email has been sent to you prior to this invoice. 
Arlington County’s Policy regarding costs is available on our website here. 
Payment can be made electronically through your Customer Portal or by clicking here . Please be aware that for all payment methods, except for an eCheck/Bank Account, that a one-time service fee 2.35% of the total invoice will be applied.

2100 Clarendon Blvd. Suite 403 
Arlington, VA 22201

communications.subject: [Records Center] County Records Request :: C006011-041625
communications.communication:
--- Please respond above this line --- 
RE: County Records Request of April 16, 2025, Reference # C006011-041625 Dear Tom Nash, Arlington County received a public records request from you on April 16, 2025. Your request mentioned: To Whom It May Concern: 

Pursuant to the Virginia Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records: 

For the multifamily property known as Crystal Towers and Crytal Flats located at 1600 South Eads Street and 505 18th Street South Arlington VA 22202 with Parcel ID 5-011-010, 35-011-011, 35-011-001, please provide the following information: 

Notice and summary of any open/outstanding zoning, building, and/or fire code violations, or written confirmation that none currently exist; 
Copies of Certificates of Occupancy, or if none are available, please state the reason for their absence and whether the lack of Certificates of Occupancy will result in any enforcement action; and 
Copies of any zoning approval documents, specifically a copy of the Crystal Towers Site Plan #13 and 1720 S Eads Street Site Plan #424 

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes. 

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not. 

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires. 

Sincerely, 

Tom Nash, a citizen of Virginia, in coordination with Olivia James. 

Upload documents directly: https://accounts.muckrock.com/accounts/login/?next=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.muckrock.com%2Faccounts%2Flogin%2F%3Fnext%3D%252Faccounts%252Fagency_login%252Farlington-county-government-17944%252Frecords-request-eads-and-18th-street-south-185058%252F%253Femail%253DFOIAOfficer%252540arlingtonva.us&url_auth_token=AAGgWdN0DB1Cp5p-bd2Fh8LzoMQ%3A1u59SY%3A2YLx5KiJiv1-s1AUxXdyj3XDAbOEkNpX16nNd4MRgEk Arlington County is in receipt of your request for records made in accordance with the Virginia Freedom of Information Act (§ 2.2-3700 et seq.). Please be advised that portions of the records you have requested relating to social security numbers are exempt from disclosure under Virginia Code Section 2.2-3815(A). Please log in to the FOIA Center at the following link to retrieve the responsive records. County Records Request - C006011-041625  For questions or additional information, please reply to this email. Sincerely, Rachel Healy, FOIA Officer 
Arlington County - Office of the County Attorney 
2100 Clarendon Blvd., Suite 403 Arlington, VA  22201 
(C) 703.843.0687 (T) 703.228.310

title: Miller v. City of LaFollette settlement agreement

communications.subject: Tennessee Public Records Act Request: Miller v. City of LaFollette settlement agreement
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Tennessee Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

A copy of the settlement agreement involving Sgt. Marvin Miller and Lt. Brian Tiller, or otherwise settling Miller v. City of LaFollette, TN, No. 3:23-cv-152.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 7 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Kent Hoover, a citizen of Tennessee, in coordination with Adam Steinbaugh.

communications.subject: Virginia Freedom of Information Act Request: Records Request - 320 23rd Street South
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Virginia Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

For the multifamily property known as Quimby on 23rd located at 320 23rd Street South Arlington VA 22202 with Parcel ID 34-020-030, please provide the following information:

Notice and summary of any open/outstanding zoning, building, and/or fire code violations, or written confirmation that none currently exist;
Copies of Certificates of Occupancy, or if none are available, please state the reason for their absence and whether the lack of Certificates of Occupancy will result in any enforcement action; and
Copies of any zoning approval documents, specifically a copy of the National Center Site Plan #65.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Tom Nash, a citizen of Virginia, in coordination with Olivia James.

    The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

Pursuant to your request to receive an estimate in advance, attached is your estimate. No payment is required at this time. 
Please review the estimate and respond to this email letting us know if you accept the charges and wish for us to continue processing your request. If you accept the estimate, a final invoice will be sent to you at the same time as the County’s response to your request.

For the multifamily property known as Quimby on 23rd located at 320 23rd Street South Arlington VA 22202 with Parcel ID 34-020-030, please provide the following information:

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Don Bailey

communications.subject: New Jersey Open Public Records Act Request: Evergreen Solutions (Middlesex County College)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New Jersey Open Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

To Whom It May Concern:


Subject: Request for Public Records - 

Greetings,

I hope this email finds you well. We at Evergreen Solutions, LLC, are conducting a compensation study on behalf of our client and I am writing to make a formal open records request. We are requesting an electronic copy of your staff and faculty (if applicable) database as well as relevant documents such as job descriptions, collective bargaining agreements, and pay plans. I am able to send survey templates to assist with the data collection; however, we will accept data in the manner most convenient for you.

Staff Census Information requested:

Job Titles
Classification Title
Pay Grades
Pay Ranges (Minimum and Maximum)
Actual Salaries
Full-Time Equivalent (FTE) Status
Staff Handbook

I also kindly request answers to the following questions related to the compensation study:

How are salaries adjusted for your organization (e.g., COLA, Longevity, performance, etc.)?
What is your current turnover rate?
What is your current average tenure for an employee?
Date your current compensation plan was implemented.
Date of the last salary adjustment?
How frequently are job descriptions updated?

For the faculty database, I am requesting the following information:

Faculty Census:
Rank (if applicable)
Classification Title (if faculty holds other positions other than teaching such as Dean, Chair, Coordinators,etc)
Highest Degree Held
Pay Grade
Pay Ranges (Min& Max)
Current Step (if on a step plan)
Contract Length (in days and/or months)
Annual Base Salary with no additives
Annual Salary with any additives
Discipline (Not to be confused with department, the distinct/specific subject the faculty member teaches; Ex: Microbiology)
Department
CIP Code (if available - by individual incumbent)

Additionally, copies of the following documents, if available:

Copy of all faculty pay plans
Employee Benefit Information (Holidays Off, Health Insurance, Etc)
Salary Adjustment Policy (Longevity, performance, COLA, etc)
Any Collective Bargaining Agreements
Current Turnover Rate
Current Average Tenure
Date that your current pay plan was implemented
Date of your last salary adjustment to pay plan
How frequently are your job descriptions updated
Do you have a planned salary adjustment to your compensation structures for the next fiscal year? If so, by what amount?
Please list/attach and supplements/additives that faculty are compensated for duties outside of instruction
Faculty Handbooks
Adjunct Rates/Pay Plan
Overload Rates
Rates for compensation for faculty leadership- Deans, Coordinators, Department Chairs
Do you compensate faculty differently based on area of discipline? If yes, please provide details.
Do you have any form of additional compensation for Large Class Size? If yes, please provide details.
Do you have an education incentive at your institution? If yes, please provide details.

I understand that public records requests may involve administrative processes and associated fees, as allowed by law. Please inform me of any fees and the estimated timeframe for fulfilling this request. If any portion of this request is denied, please provide a written explanation for the denial, citing the specific legal grounds for the refusal.

Please consider this email as a formal request for public records under the applicable open records laws. If there are any questions or additional details needed to process this request, please do not hesitate to contact me.

I look forward to your prompt attention to this matter and the timely provision of the requested information. Your cooperation in ensuring transparency and access to public records is greatly appreciated.

Do you agree to the redaction of information that is subject to mandatory exceptions, provided such redactions are clearly labeled on information you receive?: Yes
Do you agree to the redaction of information that is subject to discretionary exceptions, provided such redactions are clearly labeled on information you receive? Yes

Email: alisia@consultevergreen.com

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 7 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Alisia Rios

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: FBI Minutemen 11.22.21
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

You are receiving this correspondence as a request under the Freedom of Information Act, 5 U.S.C. subsection 552. I am requesting the following:

All bureau files covering investigations into the Minutemen organization in the following cities: Chicago (105-11643), Los Angeles (62-5101), Miami (105-4921), Phoenix (105-1226), and San Diego (100-12461). The Minutemen were a right-wing paramilitary group founded in June 1960 by businessman Robert Bolivar DePugh and operated in some capacity in cities throughout the United States between 1960 and 1969. The Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) has already made public files on Robert Bolivar DePugh and Minutemen operations in cities like New York City, so I am asking the FBI provide copies of files on these additional cities so the public may have a greater understanding of this organization and its place within the social unrest of the sixties.

Please conduct a search of the Central Records System, including but not limited to the Electronic Surveillance (ELSUR) Indices, the Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) Indices, the Physical Surveillance (FISUR) Indices, and the Technical Surveillance (TESUR) Indices, for both main-file records and cross-reference records.

I am a member of the news media, and I am asking you waive any fees associated with this request. I have written for Philly Voice and Atlas Obscura. Please take note of the Office of Management and Budget guidelines published March 27, 1987 (52 FR 10012) that include electronic publications and other nontraditional publishers as representatives of the news media.

This request is not being made for commercial purposes. All documents will be provided to the general public without charge.

In the event that there are fees, I am willing to pay up to $250. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

I look forward to your response within 20 working days, as the statute requires. If access to the records I am requesting will take longer, please contact me with information about when I might expect copies or the ability to inspect the requested records.

If you deny any or all of this request, please cite each specific exemption you feel justifies the refusal to release the information and notify me of the appeal procedures available to me under the law.

Sincerely,

Robert Skvarla, Jr.

communications.subject: RE: [EXTERNAL EMAIL] -  RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1510574-000
communications.communication:
Good morning,

Thank you for contacting foipaquestions@fbi.gov.  Please check the status of your FOIPA Request at http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on "Check Status of Your FOI/PA Request" on the right side of the page, and follow the instructions below.

Check the Status of Your FOIPA Request
If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-0] please enter [1234567-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-1] please enter [1234567-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000

Case Type:
FOIPA

Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)
The FBI's FOIPA Program is searching the FBI's indices for potentially responsive documents.
You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.

Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Complex requests are further divided into medium, large, and extra-large sub-tracks based upon request size.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  Currently, simple track cases average approximately 152 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Our complex requests in the medium processing track are currently averaging 922 days, large processing track are currently averaging approximately 1,964 days, and extra-large processing track are currently averaging 2,360 days for processing.

Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
FBI - Information Management Division
200 Constitution Drive
Winchester, VA  22602
O: (540) 868-4593
E: foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>

Do you have further questions about the FOI/PA process? Visit us at http://www.fbi.gov/foia

Please check the status of your request online at https://vault.fbi.gov/fdps-1/@@search-fdps    Status updates are performed on a weekly basis.

Note:  This is a non-emergency email address.  If this is an emergency, please call 911 directly.  If you need to report a tip for immediate action, please contact FBI Tips at http://tips.fbi.gov/ or reach out to your local field office.

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1510574-000
communications.communication:
To FOIA Appeals Officer:

You are receiving this correspondence as a request under the Freedom of Information (FOIA) Act, 5 U.S.C. subsection 552. I am appealing the following:

On November 22, 2022, I submitted Freedom of Information/Privacy Acts (FOIPA) request number 1510574-000 via MuckRock seeking all Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) records on the Chicago chapter of paramilitary group the Minutemen. At that time, I included the chapter’s Bureau file number (105-11643) for reference purposes.

On June 16, 2022, I received a response letter from the FBI releasing only one page from the chapter’s Bureau file and rejecting the rest of my request. The rejection letter cited FOIA exemptions (b)(3) 50 U.S.C., § 3024 (i)(1), (b)(6), (b)(7)(c), and (b)(7)(e). I am appealing these exemptions for the following reasons:

(b)(6) and (b)(7)(c): Exemptions (b)(6) and (b)(7)(c) are written to protect the rights of individuals against a clear and unwarranted “invasion of personal privacy,” with (b)(6) specifically covering personnel and medical files. First, I am not requesting personnel or medical files; I am asking for files from investigations into a right-wing paramilitary group. I believe exemption (b)(6) may have been included in error and request a review of this exemption.

Next, persons and groups may retain privacy rights under some circumstances, but, per the United States Court of Appeals, District Columbia Circuit, in Fund for Constitutional Government v. National Archives & Records Service, these rights yield “where exceptional interests militate in favor of disclosure.” Through actions and public statements made by Minuteman founder Robert Bolivar DePugh, the Minutemen and any subsequent chapters have no expectations of privacy because they are figures of exceptional public interest. Mr. DePugh spoke at length with newspapers about the group and participated in an unofficial biography, published in 1968 under the title "The Minutemen" (later re-released in 1969 as "A Private Army").

Additionally, the FBI has already released files on Robert Bolivar DePugh and the Minutemen to researcher John Greenwald, Jr. in 2018, as part of FOIPA request number 1415062-000 (attached under "1510574-000 Appeal Documents"). Other files on the New York City chapter were released to researcher Ernie Lazar prior to that (attached under "1510574-000 Appeal Documents"). These documents are publicly accessible in a variety of formats as of the writing of this appeal; Mr. Greenwald’s can be found on his site, The Black Vault, while Mr. Lazar’s are collected at the Internet Archive. Privacy concerns cannot be re-extended to figures where they have already been waived or determined no longer applicable.

(b)(3) 50 U.S.C., § 3024 (i)(1) and (b)(7)(e): These exemption cover information that disclose “intelligence sources and methods” and “techniques and procedures for law enforcement investigations or prosecutions, or would disclose guidelines for law enforcement investigations or prosecutions if such disclosure could reasonably be expected to risk circumvention of the law." However, these would not apply as the group in question, the Minutemen, ceased operations and disbanded in the 1970s. Although individuals may have claimed to revive the group at various points since then, there are no active chapters of the Minutemen at this time. The group’s founder, Robert Bolivar DePugh, passed away on June 30, 2009 (attached as "Minuteman outlasted notoriety..."). In the absence of a functioning body and the death of Mr. DePugh, the release of these files would not risk circumvention of the law by any living parties.

Many of the intelligence sources for the FBI have also been disclosed elsewhere. These individuals include: Michael Desmond Sadewhite, who served as a Bureau informant from 1966 until 1967 (attached under "1510574-000 Appeal Documents"); Henry Edward Warren, who disclosed information on the Minutemen from 1966 to 1968; and Jerry Milton Brooks, who testified against Mr. DePugh in 1966 and later claimed to have worked as an informant for both the FBI and then-Alcohol and Tobacco Tax Unit. These individuals have all been identified publicly in newspaper articles during the 1960s and 1970s or in J. Harry Jones’s book "The Minutemen".

Also, as previously mentioned, documents containing information about Mr. DePugh and the Minutemen have been released in other FOIPA releases in the past. Any concerns over disclosures with regard to intelligence sources or law enforcement investigation techniques or methods would have been voided upon the release of those documents.

Finally, I am renewing my request for a fee waiver. I am a member of the news media, with bylines including CovertAction Magazine, Janata Weekly, and Philly Voice. Please take note of the Office of Management and Budget guidelines published March 27, 1987 (52 FR 10012) that include electronic publications and other nontraditional publishers as representatives of the news media.

Thank you for your prompt response to this appeal. I appreciate the work that the FBI's Information Management Division does in processing FOIA requests and disseminating eligible material. As provided in 5 U.S.C. subsection 552(a)(6)(A)(ii), I anticipate that you will produce responsive documents within twenty (20) working days of receipt of this appeal.

Sincerely,
Robert Skvarla, Jr.

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1510700-000
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

I recently received two letters, attached, from Michael G. Seidel, Section Chief of the Record/Information Dissemination Section, Information Management Division, inquiring if I would like to continue with FOIPA requests 1510698-000 and 1510700-000, for information on the Minutemen organiation. Please consider this communication confirmation of my intention to continue with these requests. No circumstances have changed on my end, and I am still very much interested in obtaining these records.

I would also like to take this opportunity to renew my request for a fee waiver. My bylines include Unicorn Riot, Covert Action Magazine, and the Geopolitical Economy Report and I am sending this request in coordination with Muckrock, an award-winning and nationally-recognized news organization. Please take note of the Office of Management and Budget guidelines published March 27, 1987 (52 FR 10012) that include electronic publications and other nontraditional publishers as representatives of the news media.

Thank you for your guidance through the FOIPA process. I greatly appreciate the work the FBI's Information Management Division does in reviewing and releasing all eligible records.

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Roy Den Hollander
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

1.) Any and all records mentioning, referencing, or concerning Roy Den Hollander (September 26, 1947 - July 20, 2020). 

Roy Den Hollander was an American lawyer who gained notoriety as a suspected murderer after acting as an attorney in several unsuccessful sex discrimination suits on behalf of men. He was, allegedly, also a private investigator in Russia (Kroll Associates Russia).

Den Hollander, who had earlier stated he was "dying from cancer", was found dead on July 20, 2020, outside a rental car from an apparent self-inflicted gunshot wound, which contributed to him being made a suspect in the July 2020 murder of lawyer Marc Angelucci in California and, eight days later, an attack on the family of U.S. District Judge Esther Salas in New Jersey, in which Salas's son Daniel Anderl was killed and Salas's husband, Mark Anderl, was seriously wounded.

Proof of death in links below:

https://www.cbsnews.com/news/roy-den-hollander-murder-suicide-48-hours/

https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/213865536/roy-den_hollander

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Joanne Riford

communications.subject: RE: [EXTERNAL EMAIL] -  RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1550703-000
communications.communication:
Thank you for contacting foipaquestions@fbi.gov.  Please check the status of your FOIPA Request at http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on "Check Status of Your FOI/PA Request" on the right side of the page, and follow the instructions below.

Check the Status of Your FOIPA Request
If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-0] please enter [1234567-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-1] please enter [1234567-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000

Case Type:
FOIPA

Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)
The FBI's FOIPA Program is searching the FBI's indices for potentially responsive documents.
You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.

Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Complex requests are further divided into medium, large, and extra-large sub-tracks based upon request size.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  Currently, simple track cases average approximately 98 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Our complex requests in the medium processing track are currently averaging 947 days, large processing track are currently averaging approximately 2,011 days, and extra-large processing track are currently averaging 2,360 days for processing.

Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
FBI - Information Management Division
200 Constitution Drive
Winchester, VA  22602
O: (540) 868-4593
E: foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>

Do you have further questions about the FOI/PA process? Visit us at http://www.fbi.gov/foia

Please check the status of your request online at https://vault.fbi.gov/fdps-1/@@search-fdps    Status updates are performed on a weekly basis.

Note:  This is a non-emergency email address.  If this is an emergency, please call 911 directly.  If you need to report a tip for immediate action, please contact FBI Tips at http://tips.fbi.gov/ or reach out to your local field office.

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Kathleen Autry Arrest – February 10, 2025
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting all records related to the arrest of Kathleen J. Autry on February 10, 2025, at approximately 6:20 PM, by the Clearwater Police Department in Clearwater, Florida.

According to public records, Autry was arrested and charged with the following:

Possession of Marijuana Wax

Violation of Probation – Neglect of a Child (x2)

I am specifically requesting:

The complete arrest and incident reports, including officer narratives, probable cause affidavits, and any child welfare-related documentation

Any available body-worn camera (BWC) footage recorded during the arrest

Any 911 call recordings, CAD logs, or dispatch notes related to the incident

Photographs, videos, or evidence documentation collected during the investigation

Any documentation submitted to or by the Florida Department of Children and Families (DCF) if applicable

Given the nature of the charges involving both drug possession and child neglect, this request is submitted in the public interest to better understand the law enforcement and child protection response.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Thomas Jackson

communications.subject: City of Clearwater - Records Request Confirmation PD-2025-3095

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: SWAT Call Outs (Riverside County Sheriff)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records related to SWAT call-outs:
SWAT includes SEB or any similar division at your agency
Data recorded by the department into a database or in reports that have:
- the deployment reasons/nature of each SWAT call-out (mental health, barricaded suspect, assist with federal or local partners, etc)
- any use of force, including the use of tear-gas and explosive breaching rounds
- deployment of any specialized equipment (drones, MRAPs)
- conclusion of call 
- dates
I don't need information on the who of the investigations; I need the what (use of force, specialized equipment) and why (deployment reason, conclusion of call) of each deployment. 

Please keep in native .csv if it's from a database.

Search 2024

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Joey Scott

Joey Scott 

We have located the records responsive to your request, and those records are available in the Records Request System.  Please log in to your online account to retrieve the records. 
While the responsive records were disclosed, the Department has redacted information for privacy reasons. Where non-disclosable portions of public records are “reasonably segregable” from the disclosable portions, the agency may withhold or redact the non-disclosable portions while producing the disclosable portions. Thus, redactions are permitted under the CPRA, as long as the basis for the redaction (specified exemption) is identified in the agency’s response. See Cal. Gov. Code § 7922.525(a)-(b) American Civ. Liberties Union Found’n v. Deukmejian (1982) 32 Cal.3d 440, 452-454. 
The Department has asserted the following exemptions as legal authority to redact portions of our disclosed records: 
Government Code § 7922.000 - the records in question are exempt because, under the facts of this particular case, the public interest served by not disclosing the record clearly outweighs the public interest served by disclosure of the record. 
Government Code § 7927.705, read in conjunction with Article 1, § 1 of the California Constitution provides that personal information details are subject to privacy rights that make such information exempt from disclosure. 
Please note:  any requested data not included in our disclosed records; the Department do not keep track of. 
Please consider your CPRA request closed. 

Sincerely, 

Corr. Sergeant Victoria Miara 
CPRA Unit 
Riverside County Sheriff's Office

Pursuant to the Arizona Public Records Law, I hereby request the following
records:

1. A copy of any policy concerning recognition or registration of student
organizations at your institution or at any institution within your
district.

2. A copy of any list of active or recognized student organizations at your
institution or at any institution within your district.

3. A copy of any list of contact information for active or recognized
student organizations at your institution or at any institution within your
district.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and
this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform
me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer
the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or
CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I
look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business
days.

Sincerely,

Adam Steinbaugh

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: EB-5 Investor Projects
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

All projects from 1990 to 2021 (or the latest year with complete data) that were funded by EB-5 visa investors. I request the data in the format of a spreadsheet file. Through a 2017 Department of Commerce Report(https://www.commerce.gov/sites/default/files/migrated/reports/estimating-the-investment-and-job-creation-impact-of-the-eb-5-program_0.pdf), I know that USCIS collects data on where the money goes to.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Lars Schonander

communications.subject: ICE FOIA Request 2022-ICFO-14106
communications.communication:
May 04, 2022 Andrew Free MuckRock News DEPT MR 122335, 411A Highland Ave Somerville, Massachusetts 02144-2516 RE:     ICE FOIA Case Number 2022-ICFO-14106  Dear  Free: This acknowledges receipt of your December 22, 2021, Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE), for all records pertaining to FOIA request 2021-ICFO-32710. This request includes, but is not limited to search taskings, processing notes, and communication regarding the agency’s processing and response..  Your request was received in this office on May 04, 2022. PLEASENOTE: Requesters seekingresponsive records from the U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) areencouraged to create a DHS FOIA Public Access Link (PAL) accountat: . Creating a PALaccount will allow you to directly submit your FOIA request to ICE and trackthe status of your request. In PAL, you can view your prior PAL submissions,sent correspondences, and responsive records. Although PAL is preferred, ICEFOIA will continue to accept FOIA requests via email at (https://foiarequest.dhs.gov/) https://foiarequest.dhs.gov or via regularmail at U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement, Freedom ofInformation Act Office, 500 12 ICE-FOIA@ice.dhs.gov th St. SW, STOP 5009, Washington,DC 20536-5009. Due to the increasing number of FOIA requests received by this office, we may encounter some delay in processing your request. Per Section 5.5(a) of the DHS FOIA regulations, 6 C.F.R. Part 5, ICE processes FOIA requests according to their order of receipt. Although ICE’s goal is to respond within 20 business days of receipt of your request, the FOIA does permit a 10-day extension of this time period. As your request seeks numerous documents that will necessitate a thorough and wide-ranging search, ICE will invoke a 10-day extension for your request, as allowed by Title 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(6)(B). If you care to narrow the scope of your request, please contact our office. We will make every effort to comply with your request in a timely manner. FOR COMMERCIAL REQUESTERS: Provisions of the FOIA allow us to recover part of the cost of complying with your request.  We shall charge you for records in accordance with the DHS Interim FOIA regulations as they apply to commercial requesters.  As a commercial requester, you will be charged 10 cents per page for duplication, and for search and review time at the per quarter-hour rate ($4.00 for clerical personnel, $7.00 for professional personnel, $10.25 for managerial personnel) of the searcher and reviewer.  We will construe the submission of your request as an agreement to pay up to $25.00. You will be contacted before any further fees are accrued. We have queried the appropriate program offices within ICE for responsive records. If any responsive records are located, they will be reviewed for determination of releasability. Please be assured that one of the processors in our office will respond to your request as expeditiously as possible. We appreciate your patience as we proceed with your request. 
Your request has been assigned reference number 2022-ICFO-14106. Please refer to this identifier in any future correspondence. To check the status of an ICE FOIA/PA request, please visit . Please note that to check the status of a request, you must enter the 2022-ICFO-14106 tracking number. If you need any further assistance or would like to discuss any aspect of your request, please contact the FOIA office. You may send an e-mail to ice-foia@ice.dhs.gov, call toll free (866) 633-1182, or you may contact our FOIA Public Liaison, Marcus Francis, in the same manner. Additionally, you have a right to right to seek dispute resolution services from the Office of Government Information Services (OGIS) which mediates disputes between FOIA requesters and Federal agencies as a non-exclusive alternative to litigation. If you are requesting access to your own records (which is considered a Privacy Act request), you should know that OGIS does not have the authority to handle requests made under the Privacy Act of 1974. You may contact OGIS as follows: Office of Government Information Services, National Archives and Records Administration, 8601 Adelphi Road-OGIS, College Park, Maryland 20740-6001, e-mail at ogis@nara.gov; telephone at 202-741-5770; toll free at 1-877-684-6448; or facsimile at 202-741-5769. (http://www.dhs.gov/foia-status) http://www.dhs.gov/foia-status
Regards, 

ICE FOIA Office 
Immigration and Customs Enforcement 
Freedom of Information Act Office 
500 12th Street, S.W., Stop 5009 
Washington, D.C. 20536-5009 
Telephone: 1-866-633-1182 
Visit our FOIA website at www.ice.gov/foia

communications.subject: ICE FOIA Request 2022-ICFO-15345
communications.communication:
May 10, 2022 Andrew Free MuckRock News DEPT MR 122335, 411A Highland Ave Somerville, Massachusetts 02144-2516 RE:     ICE FOIA Case Number 2022-ICFO-15345  Dear  Free: This acknowledges receipt of your December 29, 2021, Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE), for documents pertaining to All FOIA tasking, processing, appeal, and record production records created by ICE in response to ICE FOIA 2020-ICFO-63596..  Your request was received in this office on May 10, 2022. PLEASENOTE: Requesters seekingresponsive records from the U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) areencouraged to create a DHS FOIA Public Access Link (PAL) accountat: . Creating a PALaccount will allow you to directly submit your FOIA request to ICE and trackthe status of your request. In PAL, you can view your prior PAL submissions,sent correspondences, and responsive records. Although PAL is preferred, ICEFOIA will continue to accept FOIA requests via email at (https://foiarequest.dhs.gov/) https://foiarequest.dhs.gov or via regularmail at U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement, Freedom ofInformation Act Office, 500 12 ICE-FOIA@ice.dhs.gov th St. SW, STOP 5009, Washington,DC 20536-5009. Due to the increasing number of FOIA requests received by this office, we may encounter some delay in processing your request. Per Section 5.5(a) of the DHS FOIA regulations, 6 C.F.R. Part 5, ICE processes FOIA requests according to their order of receipt. Although ICE’s goal is to respond within 20 business days of receipt of your request, the FOIA does permit a 10-day extension of this time period. As your request seeks numerous documents that will necessitate a thorough and wide-ranging search, ICE will invoke a 10-day extension for your request, as allowed by Title 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(6)(B). If you care to narrow the scope of your request, please contact our office. We will make every effort to comply with your request in a timely manner. FOR COMMERCIAL REQUESTERS: Provisions of the FOIA allow us to recover part of the cost of complying with your request.  We shall charge you for records in accordance with the DHS Interim FOIA regulations as they apply to commercial requesters.  As a commercial requester, you will be charged 10 cents per page for duplication, and for search and review time at the per quarter-hour rate ($4.00 for clerical personnel, $7.00 for professional personnel, $10.25 for managerial personnel) of the searcher and reviewer.  We will construe the submission of your request as an agreement to pay up to $25.00. You will be contacted before any further fees are accrued. FOR MEDIA REQUESTERS: Provisions of the FOIA allow us to recover part of the cost of complying with your request.  We shall charge you for records in accordance with the DHS Interim FOIA regulations, as they apply to media requesters.  As a media requester, you will be charged 10 cents per page for duplication; the first 100 pages are free.  We will construe the submission of your request as an agreement to pay up to $25.00. You will be contacted before any further fees are accrued. FOR EDUCATIONAL REQUESTERS: Provisions of the FOIA allow us to recover part of the cost of complying with your request.  We shall charge you for records in accordance with the DHS Interim FOIA regulations as they apply to educational requesters.  As an educational requester, you will be charged 10 cents per page for duplication; the first 100 pages are free.  We will construe the submission of your request as an agreement to pay up to $25.00. You will be contacted before any further fees are accrued. FOR PRIVATE INDIVIDUALS AND OTHER REQUESTERS: Provisions of the FOIA allow us to recover part of the cost of complying with your request.  We shall charge you for records in accordance with the DHS Interim FOIA regulations as they apply to non-commercial requesters.  As a non-commercial requester, you will be charged 10 cents per page for duplication; the first 100 pages are free, as are the first two hours of search time, after which you will pay the per quarter-hour rate ($4.00 for clerical personnel, $7.00 for professional personnel, $10.25 for managerial personnel) of the searcher.  We will construe the submission of your request as an agreement to pay up to $25.00. You will be contacted before any further fees are accrued. We have queried the appropriate program offices within ICE for responsive records. If any responsive records are located, they will be reviewed for determination of releasability. Please be assured that one of the processors in our office will respond to your request as expeditiously as possible. We appreciate your patience as we proceed with your request. 
Your request has been assigned reference number 2022-ICFO-15345. Please refer to this identifier in any future correspondence. To check the status of an ICE FOIA/PA request, please visit . Please note that to check the status of a request, you must enter the 2022-ICFO-15345 tracking number. If you need any further assistance or would like to discuss any aspect of your request, please contact the FOIA office. You may send an e-mail to ice-foia@ice.dhs.gov, call toll free (866) 633-1182, or you may contact our FOIA Public Liaison, Marcus Francis, in the same manner. Additionally, you have a right to right to seek dispute resolution services from the Office of Government Information Services (OGIS) which mediates disputes between FOIA requesters and Federal agencies as a non-exclusive alternative to litigation. If you are requesting access to your own records (which is considered a Privacy Act request), you should know that OGIS does not have the authority to handle requests made under the Privacy Act of 1974. You may contact OGIS as follows: Office of Government Information Services, National Archives and Records Administration, 8601 Adelphi Road-OGIS, College Park, Maryland 20740-6001, e-mail at ogis@nara.gov; telephone at 202-741-5770; toll free at 1-877-684-6448; or facsimile at 202-741-5769. (http://www.dhs.gov/foia-status) http://www.dhs.gov/foia-status
Regards, 

ICE FOIA Office 
Immigration and Customs Enforcement 
Freedom of Information Act Office 
500 12th Street, S.W., Stop 5009 
Washington, D.C. 20536-5009 
Telephone: 1-866-633-1182 
Visit our FOIA website at www.ice.gov/foia
